Food systems boundaries are currently poorly defined
                    Paul Behrens 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-2935-47991,2 & Joseph Poore 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-2527-74663

Nature Food

(2025)Cite this article

Subjects

            Climate-change impactsEnvironmental impact

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

Recent efforts to understand how food systems affect planetary health are both timely and essential, and have already produced important scientific insights1,2. At the same time, as the number of published food system analyses grow, there are some emerging framings that would benefit from greater conceptual clarity to ensure that insights are interpreted consistently and applied effectively across research and policy.For instance, the planetary boundaries are global, biophysical thresholds designed to demarcate a safe operating space for humanity3. By contrast, ‘food system boundaries’, as proposed in recent work1,2, are scenario-based allocations or budgets, set by modelling assumptions often from process-based integrated assessment models (IAMs) or from literature synthesis. For IAMs specifically, these allocations reflect what is deemed feasible under modelled constraints that often represent an outcome predicated on layers of obscured assumptions, not what is biophysically ‘safe’.



